'''Jo Hyeon-woo''' ({{langx|ko|조현우}}; born 25 September 1991) is a South Korean professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[K League 1]] club [[Ulsan HD FC|Ulsan HD]] and the [[South Korea national football team|South Korea national team]].<ref name=SW>{{Soccerway|hyun-woo-cho/286390}}</ref><ref name=the18 />

==Early life==
Jo was raised by his mother and father who was a [[gymnast]] in [[Seoul]]. Jo decided to become a goalkeeper when he saw [[Kim Byung-ji]]'s lead while watching [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 France]] in elementary.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.daegufc.co.kr/board_story_clubnews01/view.php?tn=board_story_clubnews01&list_count_s=6&G_state=Y&pm=4.2.1&part_part_s=&subject_s=&content_s=Y&name_s=&writedate_s=&search_word_s=%EC%A1%B0%ED%98%84%EC%9A%B0&sid=2163&gid=&cpage=29&spage=21 |script-title=ko:2013년 새로운 친구를 소개합니다 |date=17 January 2013 |publisher=Daegu FC|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624093029/http://www.daegufc.co.kr/board_story_clubnews01/view.php?tn=board_story_clubnews01&list_count_s=6&G_state=Y&pm=4.2.1&part_part_s=&subject_s=&content_s=Y&name_s=&writedate_s=&search_word_s=%EC%A1%B0%ED%98%84%EC%9A%B0&sid=2163&gid=&cpage=29&spage=21|archive-date=24 June 2018 |language=ko}}</ref> He later said, "I was excited about playing football after watching the World Cup as I could be someone else's dream."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yonhapnews.co.kr/bulletin/2018/06/16/0200000000AKR20180616043400007.HTML |script-title=ko:[월드컵] 월드컵 보고 꿈 키운 조현우 "나도 누군가의 꿈이 되도록" |date=16 June 2018 |publisher=[[Yonhap News Agency]] |archive-date=24 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624063944/http://www.yonhapnews.co.kr/bulletin/2018/06/16/0200000000AKR20180616043400007.HTML |access-date=24 June 2018 |url-status=live |language=ko |work=연합뉴스 |author1=고미혜 }}</ref> In his fifth grade, the football coach of Shinjeong Elementary School Ham Sang-heon asked for the best goalkeeper in the schoolyard as he was worried he would not have a goalkeeper. The children pointed to Jo. The coach tested Jo by making him save several shots. This would be the beginning of his career. He has been the main goalkeeper and has played in national tournaments ever since. In response, his old coach said "It was not once or twice that teams won because of Jo's success in the [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]]".<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.footballjournal.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=7556 |script-title=ko:깜짝스타 조현우, 선수 시작은 ‘땜질용’이었다 |last=Park |first=Jae-rim |date=15 November 2017 |publisher=Football Journal |language=ko |archive-date=24 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624064907/http://www.footballjournal.co.kr/news/articleView.html?idxno=7556 |access-date=24 June 2018}}</ref>

==Club career==
After graduating from [[Sun Moon University]], Jo entered the [[2013 K League Classic|2013 K League 1]] draft and was selected by [[Daegu FC]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yeongnam.com/mnews/newsview.do?mode=newsView&newskey=20121211.010260729120001 |script-title=ko:대구FC 신인 보강 마무리 |publisher=Youngnam Ilbo |date=11 December 2012 |language=ko |access-date=12 January 2014 |archive-date=13 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140113113942/http://www.yeongnam.com/mnews/newsview.do?mode=newsView&newskey=20121211.010260729120001 |url-status=live }}</ref> He failed to prevent the relegation of his team in his first professional season, and had to compete in the [[K League 2]]. Since the 2015 season, Jo evolved into Daegu's first-choice goalkeeper and became the best goalkeeper in the K League 2. He finally helped Daegu promote to the K League 1 in 2016. He also contributed to Daegu's first [[Korean FA Cup]] title in 2018.

After a successful career in Daegu, Jo joined Ulsan Hyundai on 20 January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |script-title=ko:조현우 국가대표 골키퍼 울산 현대 이적 |url=http://www.kookje.co.kr/news2011/asp/newsbody.asp?code=0600&key=20200120.99099007777 |access-date=15 June 2020 |publisher=The Kookje Daily News |language=ko |archive-date=15 June 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200615044222/http://www.kookje.co.kr/news2011/asp/newsbody.asp?code=0600&key=20200120.99099007777 |url-status=live }}</ref> He contributed to Ulsan's three consecutive K League 1 titles from 2022 to 2024, and was named the [[K League Most Valuable Player Award|K League 1 Most Valuable Player]] in 2024. He became the second goalkeeper to win the K League 1 MVP award, following [[Lee Woon-jae]].<ref name="mvp"/>

Jo played in three group stage matches for Ulsan at the [[2025 FIFA Club World Cup]], but lost all three matches.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldfootball.net/person/pe308288/hyeon-woo-jo/ |title=Hyeon-woo Jo » Club World Cup 2025 |website=WorldFootball.net |access-date=2025-06-29}}</ref> He blocked 10 out of 11 shots on target in the last group stage match against [[Borussia Dortmund]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sofascore.com/football/match/ulsan-hd-borussia-dortmund/ydbsddd |title=Borussia Dortmund vs Ulsan HD live score, H2H and lineups |publisher=Sofascore |date=2025-06-25 |access-date=2025-06-29}}</ref> FIFA website reminded readers of his performance against [[Germany national football team|Germany]] at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]], describing him as the "German hangman".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/club-world-cup/usa-2025/articles/dortmund-fluminense-inter-monterrey-highlights-round-up |title=Dortmund, Inter top groups, Flu, Monterrey also advance |publisher=FIFA |date=2025-06-26 |access-date=2025-06-29}}</ref> Despite his effort to bring the first victory, Ulsan lost 1–0 without scoring.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Dortmund 1-0 Ulsan (Jun 25, 2025) Final Score |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/724463/ulsan-hd-borussia-dortmund |publisher=ESPN |date=25 June 2025 |access-date=26 June 2025}}</ref>

==International career==
===Early career===
In November 2015, Jo was called up for South Korea's national team by manager [[Uli Stielike]] to play in the [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification|2018 FIFA World Cup]] qualifiers against [[Laos national football team|Laos]] and [[Myanmar national football team|Myanmar]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://world.kbs.co.kr/english/news/news_Sp_detail.htm?No=114451 |title=Roster for 2nd World Cup Qualifier Announced |publisher=KBS World |date=2 November 2015 |access-date=12 July 2016 |archive-date=23 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190823072338/http://world.kbs.co.kr/english/news/news_Sp_detail.htm?No=114451 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He was selected as the national representative for the [[EAFF E-1 Football Championship]] in 2017 winning the competition's best goalkeeper award.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://hankookilbo.com/v/429d874a49b9f943f384c52da297fce5 |script-title=ko:이재성 동아시안컵 MVP, 조현우 베스트 GK 등극 |trans-title=Lee Jae-sung Dong-A San Cup MVP, Jo Hyun-woo best GK |last=Kim |first=Ui-gi |date=16 December 2017 |publisher=[[Hankook Ilbo]] |access-date=8 June 2018 |language=ko |archive-date=12 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143639/http://hankookilbo.com/v/429d874a49b9f943f384c52da297fce5 |url-status=live }}</ref>

===2018 World Cup===
In May 2018, Jo was named in South Korea's preliminary 28-man squad for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia.<ref>{{cite web |title=Revealed: Every World Cup 2018 squad – 23-man & preliminary lists & when will they be announced? |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/revealed-every-world-cup-2018-squad-23-man-preliminary-lists/oa0atsduflsv1nsf6oqk576rb |publisher=Goal |access-date=18 May 2018 |archive-date=2 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191202163541/https://www.goal.com/en-gb/amp/news/revealed-every-world-cup-2018-squad-23-man-preliminary-lists/oa0atsduflsv1nsf6oqk576rb |url-status=live }}</ref> Originally expected to be the third-choice keeper, Jo made his international debut in a major competition.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/jun/27/south-korea-germany-world-cup-group-f-match-report |title=Germany crash out of World Cup group stage after defeat to South Korea |last=Wilson |first=Jonathan |date=27 June 2018 |work=The Guardian |language=en |access-date=27 June 2018 |archive-date=8 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230308123401/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/jun/27/south-korea-germany-world-cup-group-f-match-report |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.firstpost.com/sports/fifa-world-cup-2018-south-koreas-cho-hyun-woo-once-considered-too-short-to-be-a-keeper-stands-tall-against-germany-4617061.html |title=FIFA World Cup 2018: South Korea's Cho Hyun-woo, once considered too short to be a keeper, stands tall against Germany - Firstpost |date=28 June 2018 |publisher=Firstpost |access-date=28 June 2018 |archive-date=28 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628124803/https://www.firstpost.com/sports/fifa-world-cup-2018-south-koreas-cho-hyun-woo-once-considered-too-short-to-be-a-keeper-stands-tall-against-germany-4617061.html |url-status=live }}</ref> His performances in the first two matches against [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden]] and [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] were impressive, despite both ending in defeats for South Korea. He was lauded particularly for his point-blank save against Swedish striker Marcus Berg which put him in the spotlight. Jo then played a prominent role in [[Germany national football team|Germany]]'s historic elimination from the first round of a World Cup for the first time since 1938 with a stellar performance, earning him the [[Player of the match|Man of the Match]] award.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/match/300331532/#motm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143847/https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/match/300331532/#motm |url-status=dead |archive-date=12 June 2018 |title=2018 FIFA World Cup Russia - Matches - Korea Republic - Germany |publisher=FIFA |language=en-GB |access-date=27 June 2018}}</ref> Jo made seven saves [[Clean sheet|without conceding any goals]].<ref name=the18>{{Cite news|url=https://the18.com/soccer-news/cho-hyun-woo-south-korea-goalkeeper|title='San Zusi' Has Been Replaced By 'San Cho,' South Korea's Godly Keeper|publisher=The18|access-date=27 June 2018|archive-date=27 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627203225/https://the18.com/soccer-news/cho-hyun-woo-south-korea-goalkeeper|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite this performance, South Korea learned after the match that they had been eliminated from the tournament due to [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden]] beating [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] (South Korea needed Mexico to beat Sweden to advance).<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44439270 |title=World Cup 2018: Germany out of tournament after losing to South Korea |date=27 June 2018 |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=28 June 2018 |language=en-GB |archive-date=9 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209220341/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44439270 |url-status=live }}</ref> South Korea finished ahead of Germany in Group F, placing third.

===2018 Asian Games===
Jo was named in the [[South Korea national under-23 football team|South Korean under-23 team]] for the [[Football at the 2018 Asian Games – Men's tournament|2018 Asian Games]] as an over-aged player. He appeared in two matches against [[Bahrain national under-23 football team|Bahrain]] and [[Kyrgyzstan national under-23 football team|Kyrgyzstan]] in the group stage and finalized them with clean sheets.
He also played in the round of 16 against [[Iran national under-23 football team|Iran]], but he was injured in this match. He was replaced by [[Song Bum-keun]] in the quarter-finals against [[Uzbekistan national under-23 football team|Uzbekistan]], but Song conceded three goals. Song received criticisms for his poor performance, and so Jo appeared again in semi-finals and final. He contributed to South Korea's gold medal by conceding only two goals in the tournament and was subsequently exempt from mandatory military service.

